{{technical|date=October 2013}}
{{general relativity|solutions}}

In [[general relativity]], the '''Weyl−Lewis−Papapetrou coordinates''' are a set of [[coordinates]], used in the solutions to the [[vacuum]] region surrounding an [[axisymmetric]] distribution of [[mass–energy]]. They are named for [[Hermann Weyl]], [[T. Lewis (physicist)|T. Lewis]]<!---need to confirm exactly who he is--->, and [[Achilles Papapetrou]].<ref>Weyl, H., "Zur Gravitationstheorie," ''Ann. der Physik'' '''54''' (1917), 117–145.</ref><ref>T. Lewis, "Some special solutions of the equations of axially symmetric gravitational fields," ''Roy. Soc., Proc.'' '''136''', 176–92 (May 2, 1932).</ref><ref>A. Papapetrou, "A static solution of the equations of the gravitatinal field for an arbitrary charge-distribution," ''Proc. R. Irish Acad.'' '''A 52''', 11 (1948).</ref>

==Details==
The square of the [[line element]] is of the form:<ref>{{cite book|title=Gravitation, Following the Prague Inspiration: A Volume in Celebration of the 60th Birthday of Jiří Bičák|author=Jiří Bičák|author2=O. Semerák|author3=Jiří Podolský|author4=Martin Žofka|publisher=[[World Scientific]]|page=122|date=2002|isbn=981-238-093-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hen4Bb-bjgUC&pg=PA122&lpg=PA122&dq=Weyl%E2%88%92Lewis%E2%88%92Papapetrou+coordinates&source=bl&ots=XZ0DxKeYf5&sig=as5plL8kYXPotV9kpnhlG1rpEb0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WQhuUoX8FZPwhQeknYCoCQ&ved=0CF0Q6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=Weyl%E2%88%92Lewis%E2%88%92Papapetrou%20coordinates&f=false}}</ref>

:<math>ds^2 = -e^{2\nu}dt^2 + \rho^2 B^2 e^{-2\nu}(d\phi - \omega dt)^2 + e^{2(\lambda - \nu)}(d\rho^2 + dz^2)</math>

where (''t'',&nbsp;''ρ'',&nbsp;''ϕ'',&nbsp;''z'') are the cylindrical Weyl−Lewis−Papapetrou coordinates in 3&nbsp;+&nbsp;1 [[spacetime]], and ''λ'', ''ν'', ''ω'', and ''B'', are unknown functions of the spatial non-angular coordinates ''ρ'' and ''z'' only. Different authors define the functions of the coordinates differently.

